      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         <p>Don Tobin was an American animator and cartoonist. Tobin worked for the Walt Disney
            Company as an animator, though he left after its strike in 1941. He is credited as an
            effects animator for the Disney short "The Nifty Nineties" (1941) on IMDB.com and in
               <emph render="italic">The Animated Film Encyclopedia: A Complete Guide to American
               Shorts, Features and Sequences (1900-1979)</emph>. </p>
         <p>"The Nifty Nineties" stars Mickey and Minnie Mouse, who take part in an old-time
            vaudeville themed short and venture to see a movie.  The short before their film is
            "Father, Dear Father." A short-within-a-short, the "Father Dear Father" segment is a
            melodrama. Watch the short <extref href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0mLNS7CTLes&amp;feature=related">here</extref>. </p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Father, Dear Father Collection</emph> consists of original
            artwork from the Disney short "The Nifty Nineties." The collection includes 22 paper
            sketches and 17 painted animation stills, some of which are matted.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
         <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
         <p>All material from the collection is arranged by series and housed together.</p>
      </arrangement>
      <relatedmaterial encodinganalog="544 1">
         <head>Related Material</head>
         <p>Additional material from Don Tobin, including magazine cartoons and artwork from the
            comic strip <emph render="italic">The Little Woman</emph> are located in the <archref href="../t/tobin_d.htm">Don Tobin Cartoons</archref> collection.</p>
         <p>&scrc_name; has collections of more than 150 cartoonists. Please refer to &subjindex;
            for a complete listing. </p>
